You're right, it would be a good idea to include the `IsArchived` column in the stored procedure as well, in case you want to update the archived status of the template. Here's an updated version of the stored procedure that includes the `IsArchived` parameter:

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[spTemplate_Edit]
    @TemplateId INT,
    @TemplateName NVARCHAR(50),
    @IsArchived BIT
AS
BEGIN
    SET NOCOUNT ON;

    BEGIN TRY
        BEGIN TRANSACTION;

        -- Update the template name and archived status
        UPDATE Templates
        SET TemplateName = @TemplateName,
            IsArchived = @IsArchived
        WHERE TemplateId = @TemplateId;

        COMMIT TRANSACTION;
    END TRY
    BEGIN CATCH
        ROLLBACK TRANSACTION;
        THROW;
    END CATCH
END
```

In this updated version, we've added the `@IsArchived` parameter of type `BIT` (0 for not archived, 1 for archived). The `UPDATE` statement now updates both the `TemplateName` and `IsArchived` columns for the specified `TemplateId`.

To use this stored procedure, you would call it like this:

```sql
EXEC [dbo].[spTemplate_Edit] @TemplateId = 1, @TemplateName = 'New Template Name', @IsArchived = 0;
```

This will update the template with the ID of 1, set its name to 'New Template Name', and mark it as not archived (0).

By including the `IsArchived` parameter, you can easily update the archived status of a template along with its name in a single stored procedure call.

Yes, you can leave out the `@IsArchived` parameter from the stored procedure call if you don't want to update the `IsArchived` status of the template. The stored procedure will then only update the `TemplateName` column and leave the `IsArchived` column unchanged.

Here's the updated stored procedure with the `@IsArchived` parameter marked as optional:

```sql
CREATE PROCEDURE [dbo].[spTemplate_Edit]
    @TemplateId INT,
    @TemplateName NVARCHAR(50),
    @IsArchived BIT = NULL
AS
BEGIN
    SET NOCOUNT ON;

    BEGIN TRY
        BEGIN TRANSACTION;

        -- Update the template name and archived status (if provided)
        UPDATE Templates
        SET TemplateName = @TemplateName,
            IsArchived = ISNULL(@IsArchived, IsArchived) -- Keep the existing value if @IsArchived is NULL
        WHERE TemplateId = @TemplateId;

        COMMIT TRANSACTION;
    END TRY
    BEGIN CATCH
        ROLLBACK TRANSACTION;
        THROW;
    END CATCH
END
```

In this version, the `@IsArchived` parameter is marked as optional by providing a default value of `NULL`. In the `UPDATE` statement, we use the `ISNULL` function to check if `@IsArchived` is `NULL`. If it is `NULL`, we keep the existing value of the `IsArchived` column; otherwise, we update it with the provided value.

To update only the `TemplateName` without changing the `IsArchived` status, you can call the stored procedure like this:

```sql
EXEC [dbo].[spTemplate_Edit] @TemplateId = 1, @TemplateName = 'New Template Name';
```

Since the `@IsArchived` parameter is not provided, it will be treated as `NULL`, and the `IsArchived` column will not be updated.

If you want to update both the `TemplateName` and `IsArchived` status, you can call the stored procedure with all three parameters:

```sql
EXEC [dbo].[spTemplate_Edit] @TemplateId = 1, @TemplateName = 'New Template Name', @IsArchived = 0;
```

This way, you have the flexibility to update either or both columns as needed.
